Restricted business activities are generally the same as ones the FRE itself may not undertake. These activities include Footnote 25 :
  1. certain personal property leasing in Canada;
  2. uninsured high ratio residential mortgage lending in Canada;
  3. acting as a trustee in Canada, unless the OE acts as a trustee only with respect to a closed-end fund or a mutual fund entity, in accordance with provincial laws;
  4. dealing in securities, except as may be permitted to the FRE, a mutual fund entity, a mutual fund distribution entity or a closed-end fund;
  5. insurance business, where both the FRE is not governed by the ICA, and the OE engages in the activities of a finance entity;
  6. in the case of a property and casualty company, a marine company and a fraternal benefit society, either financial intermediary activities that expose the OE to material market or credit risk, or the activities of a specialized financing entity;
  7. acquiring control of, or acquiring or holding a substantial investment in, another entity unless: in the case of an OE that will be controlled by the FRE, the FRE itself would be permitted to acquire a substantial investment in the other entity, or in the case of an OE that will not be controlled by the FRE, the FRE itself would be permitted to acquire a substantial investment in the other entity as either: a PE, without regard to any approval or control requirement Footnote 26 , an “investment via an RE subsidiary” (see Section 4 below for more information), an entity whose shares or ownership interests are held for a limited period of time as a result of either a loan workout or the realization of a security interest (see Section 5 below for more information), or an entity whose shares or ownership interests are held in accordance with the Specialized Financing Regulations Footnote 27 (see Section 6 below for more information); and
  8. the business of accepting deposit liabilities.
  1. the FRE is not governed by the ICA, and
  2. the OE engages in the activities of a finance entity;
  1. financial intermediary activities that expose the OE to material market or credit risk, or
  2. the activities of a specialized financing entity;
  1. in the case of an OE that will be controlled by the FRE, the FRE itself would be permitted to acquire a substantial investment in the other entity, or
  2. in the case of an OE that will not be controlled by the FRE, the FRE itself would be permitted to acquire a substantial investment in the other entity as either: a PE, without regard to any approval or control requirement Footnote 26 , an “investment via an RE subsidiary” (see Section 4 below for more information), an entity whose shares or ownership interests are held for a limited period of time as a result of either a loan workout or the realization of a security interest (see Section 5 below for more information), or an entity whose shares or ownership interests are held in accordance with the Specialized Financing Regulations Footnote 27 (see Section 6 below for more information); and
  1. a PE, without regard to any approval or control requirement Footnote 26 ,
  2. an “investment via an RE subsidiary” (see Section 4 below for more information),
  3. an entity whose shares or ownership interests are held for a limited period of time as a result of either a loan workout or the realization of a security interest (see Section 5 below for more information), or
  4. an entity whose shares or ownership interests are held in accordance with the Specialized Financing Regulations Footnote 27 (see Section 6 below for more information); and
As long as an FRE controls, or holds a substantial investment in, an OE, the OE’s business activities are subject to these restrictions.

As discussed in Subsection 3.2 above, subject to complying with the minority investment limits, an FRE may generally only acquire a substantial investment in:
  1. an RE;
  2. an investment holding entity; or
  3. an OE that engages in financial intermediary activities that expose the OE to material marketor credit risk;
if the FRE also acquires control in fact of the entity.
Where an FRE controls in fact such an entity and seeks to give up control while keeping a substantial investment in the entity, the FRE generally requires the Superintendent’s approval to do so Footnote 41 .
